Abstract

In multi-level modeling, it is very common to subdivide the data into subgroups for the creation of graphs. The trellis plot, poineered by Wm. Cleveland, was first offered in S+. Since then, many programs have implemented functions to generate this same type of plot.

Example data

The High School and Beyond data set summarizes mathematical and English language achievement for students. I have instructions about downloading and importing that data on this web page:

http://pj.freefaculty.org/guides/stat/DataSets/HSB/00-README.txt

The following will download a copy of the data if one is not already available in the working directory.

if (file.exists("hsb.rds")){
    hsb <- readRDS("hsb.rds")
} else {
    library(foreign)
    hsb.url <- "http://www.stata-press.com/data/mlmus3/hsb.dta"
    hsb <- read.dta(hsb.url)
    saveRDS(hsb, "hsb.rds")
}
hsb$schoolidf <- factor(hsb$schoolid)

R packages for trellis plots

1 coplot in base R. Syntax: y ~ x | z, where z is the grouping variable.

#coplot(mathach ~ ses | schoolidf, hsb)

Choose sample of 27 schools

#id27 <- sample(x = unique(hsb$schoolid), size = 27)
#hsbsub <- hsb[hsb$schoolid %in% id27, ] 
#coplot(mathach ~ ses | schoolidf, hsbsub)

Now unused levels in schoolidf must be dropped for purpose of analysis

id27 <- sample(x = unique(hsb$schoolid), size = 27)
hsbsub <- hsb[hsb$schoolid %in% id27, ]
hsbsub$schoolidf <- factor(hsbsub$schoolidf)
coplot(mathach ~ ses | schoolidf, hsbsub)

2 lattice package

Fearing that usage of the name trellis might invite either confusion or complaint from ATT, the early R facility to do same sort of graph was named lattice. Development work was done by U. Wisconsin Deepayan Sarkar, who wrote a book about it named Lattice: Multivariate Data Visualization with R (Springer, 2008).

The workhorse function for 2D plots is xyplot.

library(lattice)
xyplot(mathach ~ ses | schoolidf, hsbsub)

xyplot(mathach ~ female | schoolidf, hsbsub)

The style of the presentation is patterned after the original ATT trellis graphs:

  1. School ID printed in small title box for each display
  2. default plot for numeric variables is a scatterplot
  3. Tightly placed subplots with no space between
  4. Re-use axes to avoid clutter

The design of the lattice function is intricate. It is possible to add features within each panel.

Like R base plots, xyplot will try to detect the variable types being used and adjust accordingly. Note the difference between the xyplot using female as a numeric variable code 0 or 1

xyplot(mathach ~ female | schoolidf, hsbsub)

and the xyplot in which the factor gender is used.

hsbsub$gender <- factor(hsbsub$female, levels = c(0,1), labels = c("male", "female"))
xyplot(mathach ~ gender | schoolidf, hsbsub)

Please read the manual, ?xyplot. As one can see, there is a very elaborate design that allows one to add detailed features within each subplot.

Over the past few years, several of our graduate students have mastered lattice graphics. I have to admit, I find it rather difficult to wrap all of the required code into a single very large function call. That reluctance about lattice is somewhat widely shared, it was one of the motivations for development of alternative plotting frameworks. The leading alternative at the current time is ggplot2

  1. ggplot2

Like lattice, ggplot2 was a doctoral dissertation project. It was Hadley Wickhams thesis project at Iowa State University. It is discussed in his book,

One of the themes is that people who make graphics should be guided by a more formal, carefully elucidated framework. Hence the reliance on recommendations in the book, The Grammar of Graphics, from which the gg in the packages title eminates.

The main difference between lattice and ggplot2 is in the style with which individual plot pieces are added.

  • In lattice, one writes a single, large function call that adds all of the elements

  • ggplot2, like R base plots, allows one to add individual plot elements, one at a time.

The original ggplot syntax, to which I am still partial, resembles object oriented programming. For example

p <- ggplot(...code here...)
p <- p + ggplot_function(...more code here...)
p <- p + ggplot_function(...more code here...)

While that is my favorite way, the youngsters seem to prefer to write out the plot as a long sum of statements, like this:

p <- ggplot(...code here...)
     + ggplot_function(...more code here...)
     +  ggplot_function(...more code here...)

Stata

Stata is not my preferred graphics framework. I learned these examples by studying Rabe-Hesketh & Skrondals book, Multilevel and Longitudinal Modeling using Stata.

The Stata framework for trellis graphics is rather closer to the R lattice package than to base R graphics or ggplot2. One can create an initial plot and then add features in parentheses after that.

One interesting feature is that Stata uses the same basic command to produce a plot for a single sample and for many subsamples.

Explore twoway: Simple Scatterplot in Stata

  • Scatterplot

Suppose we have columns y, x, and yhat (predicted values from regression).

twoay (line..) versus twoway (scatter)

regress y x
predict yhat, xb
twoway (scatter y x)

  • Add a regression line

    twoway (scatter y x)(line yhat x, sort)

  • Embellish with axis titles

    twoway (scatter y x)(line yhat x, sort), ytitle(my y var is),
xtitle(my xvar is)

These examples work well if there is one sample, not separate groups. For multiple groups, we need the trellis graph

Trellis

Suppose there is a grouping variable z

add a comma, then by , by(z)

I generally do not want the extra space that inserts, so by habit I insert ,by(z compact)

twoway (scatter y x)(lfit y x, sort lpatt(solild)), ///
by(z, compact legend(off) cols(5)) ///
xtitle(whatever) ytitle(somethingelse) ysize(3) xsize(2)

Spaghetti plot

egen mn_lwage = mean(lwage), by(year) sort nr year twoway (scatter lwage year, jitter(2) msym(0) msize(tiny)) /// (line lwage year if number <= 12, connect(ascending) /// lwidth(vthin) lpatt(solid)) /// (line mn_lwage year, sort lpatt(longdash)) if lwage >-2, /// ytitle(whatever) xtitle(whatever) /// legend(order( 2 Individual 3 Mean))
